# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: edward-p-bullard-jr
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] Cohen graduated from Thomas Jefferson High School in San Antonio, Texas.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] He received a Bachelor of Science degree from Texas A&M University in 1952, a Master of Science degree from Stevens Institute of Technology in 1958, and an honorary doctorate from Stevens in 1982.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] Cohen joined NASA in 1962 and served in key leadership roles critical to the success of the flights and lunar landings of the Apollo Program.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] From 1969 to 1972, Cohen was the manager for the Apollo Command and Service Modules.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] He oversaw the design, development, production and test flights of the Space Shuttles as manager of NASA's Space Shuttle Orbiter Project Office from 1972 to 1982.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] After serving as Director of Engineering at Johnson for several years, he was named director of the center in 1986, serving in that post until 1993.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] After his retirement from NASA, Cohen taught mechanical engineering design at Texas A&M University.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/aaron-cohen-deputy-nasa-administrator] In 2000, he was appointed Professor Emeritus, and in 2010, he was awarded an honorary Doctor of Letters.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/alan-howard-engineer] Howard was born in Washington, D.C., in 1905.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/alan-howard-engineer] He obtained his BSc in electrical engineering from Purdue University in 1927.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/alan-howard-engineer] After his graduation in 1927, Howard started his lifelong career at the General Electric Company in Schenectady, New York as electrical engineer.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/alan-howard-engineer] He advanced rapidly various positions, and moved into steam turbine activities in 1941.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/alan-howard-engineer] In World War II at General Electric, Howard managed the development of aircraft gas turbine engine for the United States Air Force, and developed the TG 100 and TG 180 turboprop engine.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/alan-howard-engineer] Coffin Award by General Electric for his "accomplishments in connection with the design and development of the TG100 and TG180 aircraft gas turbines." In 1954, he was awarded the honorary degree of doctor of engineering by Purdue University.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/alan-howard-engineer] In 1962, he had been elected Fellow of the American Society of Mechanical Engineers, and in 1964, he was awarded the ASME Medal.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/albert-kingsbury] Albert Kingsbury was born in Morris, Illinois and graduated from Cuyahoga Falls High School, OH in 1880.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/albert-kingsbury] In addition to his interest in tribology and bearings, Kingsbury enjoyed the world of arts, history, and letters.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/albert-kingsbury] He devoted much time to the study of foreign languages.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury died in Greenwich, Connecticut 1943, and is buried at the Green-Wood Cemetery, Brooklyn, New York.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/albert-kingsbury] In 1884, Kingsbury attended the University of Akron to study Scientific-Latin courses.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/albert-kingsbury] He dropped out and worked as a machine apprentice in Cuyahoga Falls.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury credited this as an important experience that led him to advance his career in engineering.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury resumed his formal education at Ohio State University, but he again dropped out to work as a machinist with the Warner and Swasey Company in Cleveland.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury received his mechanical engineering degree from Cornell University in 1887.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/albert-kingsbury] It was at Cornell that he met Professor Robert Henry Thurston.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/albert-kingsbury] Professor Thurston was instrumental in shaping Kingsbury's interest in bearings and tribology.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/albert-kingsbury] Working under Professor Thurston, Kingsbury conducted tests on bearing materials for the Pennsylvania Railroad.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/albert-kingsbury] His craftsmanship, honed by his experience in machine shops, allowed Kingsbury to fit half-bushings to the journal by scraping.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/albert-kingsbury] His hand fitting produced the small tolerances that promoted film lubrication.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/albert-kingsbury] These bearings, when ran showed no measurable signs of wear, and was Kingsbury's prompt to the creation of the thrust bearings which now bear his name.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury pursued a teaching position at the University of New Hampshire.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/albert-kingsbury] Within two years, he was a professor of Mechanical Engineering courses at the university.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/albert-kingsbury] His new position at the university allowed him to continue pursuing his interest in lubrication.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/albert-kingsbury] During his time at the University of New Hampshire, he created an innovative test machine to measure friction in coarse pitch, lubricated screw threads at loads of up to 14,000 psi.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/albert-kingsbury] The usefulness of this invention received mixed reviews from the American Society of Mechanical Engineers (ASME).
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/albert-kingsbury] His research also covered fluid lubricated bearings, and he published a paper entitled "Experiments with an Air Lubricated Bearing".
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/albert-kingsbury] It was at this university that he envisioned the Kingsbury thrust bearing.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury joined the Worcester Polytechnic Institute to continue pursuing his interest in lubrication.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/albert-kingsbury] He secured expansions for laboratory facilities and funding to continue his tests on a centrally pivoted thrust bearing with the aid of his students.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury's research at the University of New Hampshire led him to conceive an early Kingsbury bearing that consisted of several stationary arc segments facing a thrust collar on the rotating shaft.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/albert-kingsbury] Each segment would have a boss on the side away from the thrust collar, allowing it to tilt and form an oil wedge that would carry the thrust.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury tested this new bearing with a modified version of his earlier screw thread testing machine.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/albert-kingsbury] The bearing was successful with pressures of up to 4,000 psi at speeds of 285 rpm.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/albert-kingsbury] This pressure exceeded that for common collar-type bearings by a factor of 80 to 100, thus proving the promise of the Kingsbury bearing.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury joined the Westinghouse Electric Company in Pittsburgh as a general engineer.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/albert-kingsbury] He used this as an opportunity to advance the development of his thrust bearings in an industrial setting.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/albert-kingsbury] Unfortunately, the first test of his thrust bearing was a failure.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/albert-kingsbury] His bearing overheated during the test and was discarded.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/albert-kingsbury] This made the company skeptical of Kingsbury's invention, but Westinghouse's skepticism did not dent Kingsbury's enthusiasm.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury would later fund his own test that proved his bearings successful.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/albert-kingsbury] Unfortunately, Westinghouse decided to stick to more conventional ball bearings for their motors.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury tried to file for a U.S. patent during 1907.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/albert-kingsbury] His initial application was rejected as a British patent had been granted in 1905 to A.G.M.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury was able to demonstrate that his 1898 test at the University of New Hampshire predated Michell's work, so in 1910 Kingsbury was awarded US patent No.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/albert-kingsbury] 947242 for the tilting pad thrust bearing.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury would eventually run his own business with the Westinghouse Machine Co. building his bearings.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/albert-kingsbury] This allowed him to actively pursue applications for his newly patented thrust bearing.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/albert-kingsbury] His first chance came when the Pennsylvania Water and Power Co. gave him the opportunity to demonstrate his bearing on their power generator at the Susquehanna River.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/albert-kingsbury] His first bearing was a failure as it was immediately destroyed by Hillson wiping.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/albert-kingsbury] Fortunately for Kingsbury, the Pennsylvania Water and Power Co. gave him a second chance.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/albert-kingsbury] His bearing succeeded this time, and worked flawlessly for the next 25 years.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/albert-kingsbury] When it was inspected after 25 years, there was so little evidence of wear that it was calculated that the bearing would last 1,300 to 1,700 years.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/albert-kingsbury] The same bearing is still operating smoothly today.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/albert-kingsbury] In 1921, the Kingsbury thrust bearing had become so popular that Westinghouse could no longer keep up with the demand, thus prompting Kingsbury to set up his own manufacturing plant.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury continued to pursue his interest in bearings and tribology later in his life.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/albert-kingsbury] One of his greatest achievements was his analysis of the effects of side leakage of lubricants from bearings.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/albert-kingsbury] By recognizing the analogy in the equations for lubrication and those for electrical flow in a conductive fluid and variable depth, Kingsbury was able to make complicated predictions of slider load capacity well before the advent of computers.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury made important contributions to the area of boundary lubrication.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/albert-kingsbury] He was the first to recognize that some fluid lubricants possess a friction-reducing property that is independent of viscosity, which he called 'oiliness'.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/albert-kingsbury] His findings were of great significance since they demonstrated that the hydrodynamic theory of lubrication did not describe completely the lubricating mechanism of fluids.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/albert-kingsbury] Later work by Hardy and Doubleday showed that this property was related to the ability of polar lubricants to adsorb and form close-packed monolayers on the sliding surfaces.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/albert-kingsbury] for his wide-ranging contributions to the field, Kingsbury was named as one of the 23 "Men of Tribology" by Duncan Dowson.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/albert-kingsbury] Kingsbury received many accolades for his contributions to science and engineering.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/albert-kingsbury] He was awarded the Gold Medal of the American Society of Mechanical Engineers in 1931; the Elliott Cresson Medal of the Franklin Institute; and honorary doctorates from the University of New Hampshire and Worcester Polytechnic Institute.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/albert-kingsbury] He was elected Honorary Member of ASME in 1940.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/albert-kingsbury] The Kingsbury Hall at the University of New Hampshire also pays homage to the great inventor.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/albert-kingsbury] Albert Kingsbury was inducted into the National Inventors Hall of Fame.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/ambrose-swasey] Swasey was born near Exeter, New Hampshire to Nathaniel and Abigail Swasey.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/ambrose-swasey] He apprenticed as a machinist at the Exeter Machine Works and was afterwards employed at Pratt & Whitney.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/ambrose-swasey] As his career progressed, he became a foreman in the gear-cutting section.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/ambrose-swasey] He developed a new technique for making gear-tooth cutters.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/ambrose-swasey] In 1880, he and Warner formed their eponymous firm, which quickly moved to Cleveland, Ohio.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/ambrose-swasey] Swasey would perform the engineering and machine development at this company.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/ambrose-swasey] The close friends Warner and Swasey built their homes next to each other on Euclid Avenue in Cleveland, a street that was known as "Millionaire's Row".
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/ambrose-swasey] In addition to army ordnance contracts, the firm of Warner & Swasey became notable for their work on astronomical observatories and equipment.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/ambrose-swasey] The founders were interested in astronomy as an avocation, and in the field's quest for better optical telescopes, which was burgeoning at the time.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/ambrose-swasey] They also realized that obtaining contracts to build large astronomical observatories would provide publicity for their company.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/ambrose-swasey] In 1885, Swasey completed work at McCormick Observatory on the 45-foot dome, which was the largest in the world, and had a unique, 3 shutter design.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/ambrose-swasey] In 1887, Swasey built the mount for the 36-inch refracting telescope at Lick Observatory.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/ambrose-swasey] In 1898, he manufactured a dividing engine for the U.S.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/ambrose-swasey] Naval Observatory that was used to make the meridian circles.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/ambrose-swasey] Both the building and dome of the Dominion Astrophysical Observatory were made by Warner and Swasey Co.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/ambrose-swasey] Other observatory telescopes and components were built by the company at the Kenwood Observatory, Yerkes Observatory, Argentine National Observatory, the Swasey Observatory at Denison University, and the Case School of Applied Science Observatory.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/ambrose-swasey] From 1904 until 1905, he was the president of the American Society of Mechanical Engineers.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/ambrose-swasey] Both Warner and Swasey were amateur astronomers.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/ambrose-swasey] When they became trustees of the Case School of Applied Science, they donated to the school their private observatory, which they had built between their neighboring houses in East Cleveland.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/ambrose-swasey] Relocated to a new building, this became the Warner and Swasey Observatory.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/ambrose-swasey] The observatory maintained by the department today is still known by this name today.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/ambrose-swasey] Swasey Hall (1917, "懷士堂"), a red brick hall, is the landmark of Sun Yat-sen University, one of the top colleges in China.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/ambrose-swasey] It was named after Swasey for his USD$25000 donation to the then university Christian YMCA society hall.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/ambrose-swasey] The chimes in the chapel were included as a memorial to his wife, Lavinia Marston Swasey.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/ambrose-swasey] The Warner & Swasey Company he cofounded would continue until 1980, when it was acquired by Bendix Corporation.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] Amherst is an exclusively undergraduate four-year institution.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] 1,914 full-time students were enrolled in fall 2024.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] Students choose courses from 42 major programs in an open curriculum and are not required to study a core curriculum or fulfill any distribution requirements; students may also design their own interdisciplinary major.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] Amherst competes in the NCAA Division III as a member of the New England Small College Athletic Conference.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] Amherst has historically had close relationships and rivalries with Williams College and Wesleyan University, which form the Little Three colleges.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] The college is also a member of the Five College Consortium, which allows its students to attend classes at four other Pioneer Valley institutions: Mount Holyoke College, Smith College, Hampshire College, and the University of Massachusetts Amherst.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] In 1812, funds were raised in Amherst for a secondary school, Amherst Academy; it opened December 1814.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] The academy incorporated in 1816, and eventually counted among its students Emily Dickinson, Sylvester Graham, and Mary Lyon (founder of Mount Holyoke College).
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] The institution was named after the town, which in turn had been named after Jeffery, Lord Amherst, a veteran from the Seven Years' War and later commanding general of the British forces in North America.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] On November 18, 1817, a project was adopted at the Academy to raise funds for the free instruction of "indigent young men of promising talents and hopeful piety, who shall manifest a desire to obtain a liberal education with a sole view to the Christian ministry".
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] This required a substantial investment from benefactors.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] During the fundraising for the project, it became clear that without larger designs, it would be impossible to raise sufficient funds.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] This led the committee overseeing the project to conclude that a new institution should be created.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] On August 18, 1818, the Amherst Academy board of trustees accepted this conclusion and began building a new college.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] Founded in 1821, Amherst College developed from Amherst Academy, first established as a secondary school.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] The college was originally suggested as an alternative to Williams College, which was struggling to stay open.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] Although Williams survived, Amherst was formed and developed as a distinct institution.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] Moore, then President of Williams College, however, still believed that Williamstown was an unsuitable location for a college.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] When Amherst College was established, he was elected its first president on May 8, 1821.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] At its opening, Amherst had forty-seven students.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] Fifteen of these had followed Moore from Williams College.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] Those fifteen represented about one-third of the total students at Amherst, and about one-fifth of the whole number in the three classes to which they belonged in Williams College.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] President Moore died on June 29, 1823, and was replaced with a Williams College trustee, Heman Humphrey.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] Williams alumni are fond of an apocryphal story ascribing the removal of books from the Williams College library to Amherst College.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] Payne declared the story false, but many still nurture the legend.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] In 1826, Edward Jones became Amherst's first Black graduate.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] Amherst grew quickly, and for two years in the mid-1830s, it was the second largest college in the United States, behind Yale.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] In 1835, Amherst attempted to create a course of study parallel to the classical liberal arts education.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] This parallel course focused less on Greek and Latin, instead emphasizing contemporary English, French, and Spanish languages, chemistry, economics, etc.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] The parallel course did not take hold and replace the classical until the next century.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] Amherst was founded as a non-sectarian institution "for the classical education of indigent young men of piety and talents for the Christian ministry" (Tyler, *A History of Amherst College*).
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] One of the hallmarks of the new college was its Charity Fund, an early form of financial aid that paid the tuition of poorer students.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] Although officially non-denominational, Amherst was considered a religiously conservative institution with a strong connection to Calvinism; the Puritans still controlled much of Massachusetts life.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] As a result, there was considerable debate in the Massachusetts government over whether the new college should receive an official charter from the state.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] A charter was not granted until February 21, 1825, as reflected on the Amherst seal.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] Religious conservatism persisted at Amherst until the mid-nineteenth century: students who consumed alcohol or played cards were subject to expulsion.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] A number of religious revivals were held at Amherst.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] Toward the end of the nineteenth century, however, the college began a transition toward secularism.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] This movement was considered to culminate in the 1949 demolition of the college church.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] Academic hoods in the United States are traditionally lined with the official colors of the school, in theory so watchers can tell where the hood wearer earned his or her degree.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] Amherst's hoods are purple (Williams' official color) with a white stripe or chevron, said to signify that Amherst was born of Williams.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] Amherst records one of the first uses of Latin honors of any American college, dating back to 1881.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] The college was an all-male school until the late 1960s, when a few female students from nearby schools in the Four-College Consortium (Amherst, Mount Holyoke, Smith, UMass) attended on an experimental basis.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] In October 1974, the faculty voted in favor of coeducation and in November 1974, the board of trustees voted to admit female students starting in the 1975–1976 school year.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] This was done while John William Ward served as president.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] In 1975, nine women who were already attending classes as part of an inter-college exchange program were admitted as transfer students.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] In June 1976, they became the first female graduates of the college.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] The college established the Black Studies Department in 1969.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] In 1973, it launched the nation's first undergraduate neuroscience program.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] In 1983, it established a Department of Asian Languages and Literatures, which was later to become the Department of Asian Languages and Civilizations.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] In 1984, on-campus fraternities were abolished.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] The former fraternity buildings, which were owned by the college, were converted into residence halls.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] The Department of Women's and Gender Studies, which later became the Department of Sexuality, Women's, and Gender Studies, was established in 1987, and the Department of Law, Jurisprudence, and Social Thought in 1993.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] In March 2013, the faculty adopted an open-access policy.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] Eight years later, the college ended its practice of legacy admissions and increased financial aid to increase access to low and middle-income students and diversify the college.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] Amherst College is located in the town of Amherst in Western Massachusetts.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] Amherst College has a total of 34 residence halls, seven of which are strictly for first year students.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] Following their first year, sophomores, juniors, and seniors have the choice to live off campus and are offered options of Themed Houses including Arts House, Russian House, and French House, however this option is only available for two years of residence.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] First-year students are required to live on campus.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] The college also owns the Emily Dickinson Museum, operated as a museum about the life and history of poet Emily Dickinson, and the Inn on Boltwood near to the main campus.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] Amherst College is reducing its energy consumption through a computerized monitoring system for lighting and the use of an efficient cogeneration facility.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] The cogeneration facility features a gas turbine that generates electricity in addition to steam for heating the campus.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] Amherst also operates a composting program, in which a portion of the food waste from dining halls is sent to a farmer in Vermont.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] Amherst College offers 41 fields of study (with 850+ courses) in the sciences, arts, humanities, mathematics and computer sciences, social sciences, foreign languages, classics, and several interdisciplinary fields (including premedical studies) and provides an unusually open curriculum.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] Students are not required to study a core curriculum or fulfill any distribution requirements and may even design their own unique interdisciplinary major.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] Freshmen may take advanced courses, and seniors may take introductory ones.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] Amherst College is accredited by the New England Commission of Higher Education.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] Forty-five percent of Amherst students in the class of 2019 were double majors.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] Amherst College has been the first college to have undergraduate departments in the interdisciplinary fields of American Studies; Law, Jurisprudence and Social Thought; and Neuroscience and has helped to pioneer other interdisciplinary programs, including Asian Languages and Civilizations.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] The Amherst library is named for long-time faculty member, poet Robert Frost.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] The student-faculty ratio is 7:1 and 84% of classes have fewer than 30 students.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] Notable faculty members include, among others, modern literature and poetry critic William H.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] News & World Report* rankings in 1987, Amherst College has been ranked ten times as the first overall among 266 liberal arts colleges in the United States, and in 2022 ranked second, behind Williams.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] In 2023, Amherst College was ranked as the best liberal arts college and 8th best college or university overall in the United States by The WSJ/College Pulse 2024 Best College Rankings.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] In 2022, Amherst was ranked as the best liberal arts college in the country by *The Wall Street Journal*.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] *Forbes* ranked Amherst College as the 24th best college or university in the United States for their 2024–25 rankings and the 16th best college or university in the United States in 2021.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] Amherst ranked 6th in the 2021 *Washington Monthly* liberal arts college rankings, which focus on contribution to the public good in three broad categories: social mobility, research, and promoting public service.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] The issue arose when a group of alumni petitioned the college trustees and President Biddy Martin to "dissociate the institution" from Arkes's "divisive and destructive" views, focusing particularly on his May 2013 comparison of homosexuality to bestiality, pedophilia and necrophilia.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] Martin disagreed, citing past debates over the college's position on the Vietnam War and apartheid in South Africa—issues on which the college initially remained silent but eventually took a public position.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] In such times, she said, colleges should "avoid taking institutional positions on controversial political matters, except in extraordinary circumstances" and should simultaneously both "protect their communities from discrimination and disrespect" and "cherish a diversity of viewpoints".
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] Amherst is a member of the Five Colleges consortium, which allows its students to attend classes at four other Pioneer Valley institutions.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] These include Mount Holyoke College, Smith College, Hampshire College, and the University of Massachusetts Amherst.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] In addition to the 850 courses available on campus, Amherst students have an additional 5,300 classes to consider through the Consortium (without paying additional tuition) and access to 8 million library volumes.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] The Five Colleges are geographically close to one another and are linked by buses that run between the campuses.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] The Five Colleges share resources and develop common academic programs.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] Museums10 is a consortium of local art, history and science museums.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] The Five College Dance Department is one of the largest in the nation.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] The joint Astronomy department shares use of the Five College Radio Astronomy Observatory, which contributed to work that won the 1993 Nobel Prize in Physics.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] The Five College Coastal and Marine Sciences Program offers an interdisciplinary curriculum to undergraduates in the Five Colleges.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] Despite its high cost of attendance – the comprehensive tuition, room, and board fee for the 2026–27 academic year was $96,360 – Amherst College meets the full demonstrated need of every admitted student.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] Roughly sixty percent of current students receive scholarship aid, and the average financial aid package award amounts to $84,590; college expenditures are approximately $140,000 per student each year.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] In July 2007, Amherst announced that grants would replace loans in all financial aid packages beginning in the 2008–09 academic year.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] Amherst had already been the first school to eliminate loans for low-income students, and with this announcement it joined Princeton University, Cornell University and Davidson College, then the only colleges to eliminate loans from need-based financial aid packages.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] Increased rates of admission of highly qualified lower income students has resulted in greater equality of opportunity at Amherst than is usual at elite American colleges.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] In the 2008–2009 academic year, Amherst College also extended its need-blind admission policy to international applicants.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] In 2021, it also eliminated preferences for students whose parents are alumni ("legacies").
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] Amherst's resources, faculty, and academic life allow the college to enroll students with a range of talents, interests, and commitments.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] Students represent 48 states, the District of Columbia, Puerto Rico, and sixty-six countries.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] The median family income of Amherst students is $158,200, with 51% of students coming from the top 10% highest-earning families and 24% from the bottom 60%.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] Ninety-eight percent of students live on campus.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] Ninety-eight percent of Amherst freshmen enrolled in Fall 2020 returned for their sophomore year; ninety-two percent of the most recent cohort graduated within six years.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] There are more than 200 student groups at Amherst.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] More than a third of the student body are members of a varsity athletics team.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] Students pursue their interests through student-led organizations funded by a student fee and distributed by the student government, including a variety of cultural and religious groups, publications, fine and performing arts and political advocacy and service groups.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] Groups include a medieval sword-fighting club, a knitting club, and a club devoted to random acts of kindness, among others.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] Community service groups and opportunities (locally—through the Center for Community Engagement, nationally, and internationally) have been a priority at Amherst and for former President Anthony Marx, who helped start a secondary school for black students in apartheid South Africa.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] One of the longstanding traditions at the college involves the *Sabrina* statue.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] Even year and odd year classes battle for possession of the historic statue, often engaging in elaborate pranks in the process.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] In 2012, President Biddy Martin began a community-wide review of the sexual misconduct and disciplinary policies at the college.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] This review was sparked by several factors, including an underground fraternity's T-shirt design that critics alleged was misogynist and an essay by Angie Epifano published in *The Amherst Student*, wherein she accused the college of inappropriate handling of a case of sexual assault.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] In January 2013, a college committee published a report noting Amherst's rate of sexual assault as similar to other colleges and universities, and making recommendations to address the problem.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] In May 2014, the Amherst board of trustees banned students from joining any underground or off-campus fraternity.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] After a complaint was filed by Epifano and an anonymous former student in November 2013, the US Department of Education opened an investigation into the college's handling of sexual violence and potential violations of Title IX.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] In May 2014, the Department of Education announced a list of 55 colleges and universities (including Amherst) currently under investigation.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] A report from Amherst College stated that 2009 to 2011, Amherst reported 35 instances of "forcible sex offenses", a term that encompasses rape, attempted rape, and lesser forms of sexual contact.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] In 2022, in response to the anonymous sharing of sexual assault experiences at Amherst College on the Instagram account @amherstshareyourstory, then President Biddy Martin announced the launch of a new comprehensive review of the issue of sexual misconduct and assault on campus.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] According to the 2023 NECHE Interim Crediting Report listening sessions and interviews were conducted, and a website for anonymous reporting of concerns was created.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] The NECHE interim report also suggested that the review was expected to be published in Spring 2023.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] However currently there has been no update or public disclosure of the 2022 review.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] In the second decade of the 21st century, the original unofficial mascot of Amherst College, Lord Jeffery Amherst, became a cause of concern in the Amherst community.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] Many sought to separate the school from the problematic legacy of Lord Jeffery Amherst, in particular his advocacy of the use of biological warfare against Native Americans.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] In May 2014, after a wild moose found its way onto the Amherst College campus and into the backyard of the house of the college president, students organized a Facebook campaign to change the mascot of the school to a moose.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] The page grew rapidly in popularity, receiving over 900 "likes" in under two weeks, and inspiring both a Twitter and Tumblr account for the newly proposed mascot.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] At the Commencement ceremony for the class of 2014, the moose mascot was mentioned by Biddy Martin in her address, and the Dining Hall served Moose Tracks ice cream in front of an ice sculpture of a moose.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] In February 2015, discussion of a mascot change continued when the editorial board of the *Amherst Student*, the college's official student-run newspaper, came out in favor of "the moose-scot".
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] In November 2015 the student body and the faculty overwhelmingly voted to vacate the mascot.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] That same month, several hundred students who staged a sit-in protest against racism at the college library included among their demands a call for the college to cease use of the Lord Jeff mascot.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] The decision to drop the mascot was made official by the college's trustees on January 26, 2016.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] In April 2017, Amherst announced that their official mascot would be the mammoth.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] Mammoths beat the other finalists "Valley Hawks", "Purple and White", "Wolves", and "Fighting Poets" in a ranked-choice election process.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] The mammoth is linked to Amherst due to the long-standing presence of a Columbian Mammoth skeleton on display in the Beneski Museum of Natural History on campus, which dated back to the 1920s excavation of the skeleton by Amherst professor Frederic Brewster Loomis in Melbourne, Florida.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] Amherst participates in the NCAA's Division III, the Eastern College Athletic Conference, and the New England Small College Athletic Conference, which includes Bates, Bowdoin, Colby, Connecticut College, Hamilton, Middlebury, Trinity, Tufts, Wesleyan, and Williams.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] Amherst is also one of the "Little Three", along with Williams and Wesleyan.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] A Little Three champion is informally recognized by most teams based on the head-to-head records of the three schools, but three-way competitions are held in some of the sports.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] Amherst claims its athletics program as the oldest in the nation, pointing to its compulsory physical fitness regimen put in place in 1860 (the mandate that all students participate in sports or pursue physical education has been discontinued).
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] Amherst and Williams played the first college baseball game July 2, 1859.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] Athletic skill plays a factor in the admissions decisions of between 28% and 35% of each incoming class.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] Amherst fields several club athletic teams, including ultimate, soccer, crew, rugby union, water polo, equestrian, mountain biking, fencing, sailing and skiing.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] Intramural sports include soccer, tennis, golf, basketball, volleyball and softball.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] The sport of Ultimate was started and named at Amherst College in the mid-1960s by Jared Kass.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] President, the current Sovereign Prince of Monaco, two Prime Ministers and one Foreign Minister of Greece, a President of Kenya, a President of El Salvador, a Chief Justice of the United States, three Speakers of the U.S.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] Poet Laureate, the legal architect of *Brown v.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] Among its alumni, faculty and affiliates are six Nobel Prize laureates and twenty Rhodes Scholars.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] President Calvin Coolidge, Chief Justice Harlan F.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] Stone, and other notable writers, academics, politicians, entertainers, businesspeople, and activists have been graduates as well.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/amherst-college] There are approximately 23,000 living alumni, of whom about 45% make a gift to Amherst each year—one of the highest alumni participation rates of any college in the country.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/asme-medal] The **ASME Medal**, created in 1920, is the highest award bestowed by the ASME (founded as the American Society of Mechanical Engineers) Board of Governors for "eminently distinguished engineering achievement".
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/asme-medal] The award has been presented every year since 1996 (first medalist was awarded in 1921), and it consists of a $15,000 honorarium, a certificate, a travel supplement not to exceed $750, and a gold medal inscribed with the words, "What is not yet, may be".
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/asme-medal] ASME also gives out a number of other awards yearly, including the Edwin F.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/asme-medal] Church Medal, the Holley medal, and the Soichiro Honda medal.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] In metalworking and woodworking, an **automatic lathe** is a lathe with an automatically controlled cutting process.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] Automatic lathes were first developed in the 1870s and were mechanically controlled.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] From the advent of NC and CNC in the 1950s, the term automatic lathe has generally been used for only mechanically controlled lathes, although some manufacturers (e.g., DMG Mori and Tsugami) market Swiss-type CNC lathes as 'automatic'.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] CNC has not yet entirely displaced mechanically automated lathes, as although no longer in production, many mechanically automated lathes remain in service.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] The term "automatic lathe" is still often used in manufacturing in its earlier sense, referring to automated lathes of non-CNC types.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] The first automatic lathes were mechanically automated and controlled by cams or tracers and pantographs.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] Thus, before electronic automation via numerical control, the "automatic" in the term "automatic machine tool" always referred implicitly to *mechanical* automation.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] The earliest mechanically automated lathes were geometric lathes, including rose engine lathes.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] In industrial contexts during the Machine Age, the term "automatic lathe" referred to mechanical screw machines and chuckers.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] Since the maturation of CNC, the implicit dichotomy of "manual versus automatic" still exists, but because CNC is so ubiquitous, the term "automatic" has lost some of its distinguishing power.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] All CNC machine tools are automatic, but the usage in the machining industries does not routinely call them by that term.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] The term "automatic", when it is used at all, still often refers implicitly to cam-operated machines.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] Thus a 2-axis CNC lathe is not referred to as an "automatic lathe" even if fully automated.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] Small- to medium-sized cam-operated automatic lathes are usually called **screw machines** or **automatic screw machines**.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] These machines work on parts that (as a rough guide only) are up to 80 millimetres (3.1 in) in diameter and 300 millimetres (12 in) in length.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] Screw machines almost invariably do *bar work*, meaning a length of bar stock passes through the spindle and is gripped by the chuck (usually a collet chuck).
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] As the part is being machined, the entire length of bar stock is rotated with the spindle.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] When the part is done, it is 'parted' from the bar, the chuck in released, the bar fed forward, and the chuck closed again, ready for the next cycle.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] The bar-feeding can happen by various means, including pulling-finger tools that grab the bar and pull or roller bar feed that pushes the bar from behind.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] Larger cam-operated automatic lathes are usually called **automatic chucking lathes**, **automatic lathes**, **automatic chuckers**, **automatics**, or **chuckers**.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] The 'chucker' part of the name comes from the workpieces being discrete blanks, held in a bin called a "magazine", and each one takes a turn at being chucked and machined.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] (This is analogous to the way that each round of ammunition in the magazine of a semi-automatic pistol gets its turn at being chambered.) The blanks are either individual forgings or castings, or they are pre-sawn pieces of billet.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] However, some members of this family of machine tools turn bar work or work on centers (e.g., the Fay automatic lathe).
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] Regarding bar work of large diameter (for example, 150 millimetres (5.9 in) or more), it is merely an academic point whether it is called "screw machine work" or just "automatic work".
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] Screw machines, being the class of automatic lathes for small- to medium-sized parts, are used in the high-volume manufacture of a vast variety of turned components.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] During the Swiss screw machining process, the workpiece is supported with a guide bushing, near the cutting tool.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] Speaking with reference to the normal definition of the term *screw machine*, all screw machines are fully automated, whether mechanically (via cams) or by CNC, which means that once they are set up and started, they continue running and producing parts with little human intervention.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] Mechanical automation came first, beginning in the 1870s; computerized control (via first NC and then CNC) came later, beginning in the 1950s.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] The name *screw machine* is somewhat of a metonym, as screw machines can make parts other than screws or that are not threaded.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] However, the archetypal use for which screw machines were named was screw-making.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] The term *screw machine* has been redefined as the technology changes.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] Any use of the term prior to the 1840s, if it occurred, would have referred ad hoc to any machine tool used to produce screws.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] That is, there would have been no established differentiation from the term *screw-cutting lathe*.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] When turret lathes were developed in the 1840s, the term *screw machine* was applied to them in overlapping usage with the term *turret lathe*.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] In 1860, when some of the movements, such as turret indexing, were mechanically automated, the term *automatic screw machine* was applied, and the term *hand screw machine* or *manual screw machine* was retronymously applied to the earlier machines.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] Within 15 years, the entire part-cutting cycle had been mechanically automated, and machines of the 1860 type were retronymously called *semi-automatic*.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] This narrow meaning of *screw machine* remained stable from about the 1890s until the 1950s.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] With the advent of NC, screw machines diverged into two classes, mechanical and NC.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] This distinction continues today with mechanical screw machines and CNC screw machines.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] However, in shop-floor jargon, the term *screw machine* by itself is still often understood in context to imply a mechanical screw machine, so the retronym *mechanical screw machine* is not consistently used.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] An automatic chucking machine is similar to an automatic screw machine; both use spindles in production.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] The use of spindles, which are able to drill, bore and cut the workpiece, allows several functions simultaneously on both machines.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] A key difference between the machines is that the automatic chucker handles larger work, which due to its size is more often chucking work and less often bar work.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] The Fay automatic lathe was a variant that specialized in turning work on centers.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] While a screw machine is limited to around 80 millimetres (3.1 in) practice, automatic chuckers are available that can handle up to 300 millimetres (12 in) chucks.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] Many of these machines are multispindle (more than one main spindle).
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] Well-known brands of such machines have included National-Acme, Hardinge, New Britain, New Britain-Gridley, Acme-Gridley, Davenport, Bullard Mult-Au-Matic (a vertical multispindle variant), and Thomas Ryder and Son.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] Automatic chuckers are a class of machine tool specialized to narrow industry niches, such as OEM part suppliers to the automotive industry.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] They are limited in their economic niches to high-volume production of large parts, which tends to occur only at relatively few companies (compared to smaller work that may be done by small businesses).
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] The market for such machine tools does not generally include local job shops or tool and die shops.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] Cam-operated chuckers are fading into history faster than most other non-CNC machine tool classes.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] This is because the few companies that have them tend to be forced to continually adapt to the latest state of the art (today all CNC) to compete and survive.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] Cam-op chuckers may be more likely to be scrapped than other types of non-CNC machine tools.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] Unlike with "Grandpa's South Bend lathe" or "Dad's old Bridgeport knee mill", virtually no one can afford to keep and use them for sentimental reasons alone.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] As with most nondigital commercial typesetting machinery (such as Linotype machines).
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] Mechanical screw machines have been replaced to some extent by CNC lathes (turning centers) and CNC screw machines.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] However, they are still commonly in operation, and for high-volume production of turned components it is still often true that nothing is as cost-efficient as a mechanical screw machine.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] In the hierarchy of manufacturing machines, the screw machine sits at the top when large product volumes are needed.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] An engine lathe sits at the bottom, taking the least time to set up but the most skilled labor and time to actually produce a part.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] A turret lathe has traditionally been one step above an engine lathe, needing greater set-up time but being able to produce a higher volume of product and usually requiring a lower-skilled operator once the set-up process is complete.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] Screw machines may require an extensive set-up, but once they are running, a single operator can monitor the operation of several machines.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] The advent of the CNC lathe (or more properly, CNC turning center) has blurred these distinct levels of production to some extent.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] The CNC turning center most appropriately fits in the mid-range of production, replacing the turret lathe.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] However, it is often possible to produce a single component with a CNC turning center more quickly than can be done with an engine lathe.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] To some extent too, the CNC turning center has stepped into the region traditionally occupied by the (mechanical) screw machine.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] CNC screw machines do this to an even greater degree, but they are expensive.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] In some cases they are vital, yet in others a mechanical machine can match or beat overall performance and profitability.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] It is not unusual for cam-op automatic lathes to beat CNCs on cycle time.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] CNC offers many benefits, not least CAD/CAM integration, but the CNC itself usually does not give any inherent speed advantage within the context of an automatic lathe cycle in terms of speeds and feeds or tool-changing speed.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] There are many variables involved in answering the question of which is best for a particular part at a particular company.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] (Overhead is part of the calculation—not least because most cam-op machines are long since paid for, whereas a late-model CNC machine has hefty monthly payments).
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] Businesses relying on cam-op machines are still competing even in today's CNC-filled environment; they just need to be vigilant and smart about keeping it that way.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] In the multispindle segment, some machine tool builders also build hybrid machines that are part CNC and part old-school control (some stations are CNC while others are cam-op or actuated with simple hydraulic cycles).
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] This lets shops with certain mixes of work derive competitive advantage from the lower cost compared with all-CNC machines.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] An automatic lathe may have a single spindle or multiple spindles.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] Each spindle contains a bar or blank of material that is being machined simultaneously.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] The cage that holds these six bars of material indexes after each machining operation is complete.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] The indexing is reminiscent of a Gatling gun.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] Each station may have multiple tools that cut the material in sequence.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] The tools are usually arranged in several axes, such as turret (rotary indexing), horizontal slide (linear indexing), and vertical slide (linear indexing).
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] The operation of all these tools is similar to that on a turret lathe.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] By way of example: a bar of material is fed forward through the spindle.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] The face of the bar is machined (facing operation).
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] The outside of the bar is machined to shape (turning operation).
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] The bar is drilled or bored, and finally, the part is cut off (parting operation).
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] In a single-spindle machine, these four operations would most likely be performed sequentially, with four cross-slides each coming into position in turn to perform their operation.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] In a multi-spindle machine, each station corresponds to a stage in the production sequence through which each piece is then cycled, all operations occurring simultaneously, but on different pieces of work, in the manner of an assembly line.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] For the machining of complex shapes, it is common to use form tools.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] This contrasts with the cutting that is performed on an engine lathe where the cutting tool is usually a single-point tool.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] A form tool has the form or contour of the final part but in reverse, so it cuts the material leaving the desired component shape.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] This contrasts to a single-point tool, which cuts on one point at a time and the shape of the component is dictated by the motion of the tool rather than its shape.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] Unlike on a lathe, single-point threading is rarely if ever performed; it is too time-consuming for the short cycle times that are typical of screw machines.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] A self-releasing die head can rapidly cut or roll-form threads on outside diameters.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] A non-releasing tap holder with a tap can quickly cut inside diameters but it requires single spindle machines to reverse into high speed in order for the tap to be removed from the work.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] Threading and tapping speed (low speed) is typically 1/5 the high speed.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] Rotary broaching is another common operation.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] The broach holder is mounted stationary while its internal live spindle and end cutting broach tool are driven by the workpiece.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] As the broach is fed into or around the workpiece, the broach's contact points are constantly changing, easily creating the desired form.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] The most common form made this way is a hexagonal socket in the end of a cap screw.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] The history of automatic lathes in industrial contexts began with screw machines, and that history can only be truly understood within the context of screw making in general.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] Thus the discussion below begins with a simple overview of screw making in prior centuries, and how it evolved into 19th-, 20th-, and 21st-century practice.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] Humans have been making screws since ancient times.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] For most of those centuries, screw making generally involved custom cutting of the threads of each screw by hand (via whittling or filing).
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] Other ancient methods involved wrapping wire around a mandrel (such as a stick or metal rod) or carving a tree branch that had been spirally wrapped by a vine.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] Various machine elements that potentially lent themselves to screw making (such as the lathe, the leadscrew, the slide rest, gears, slide rests geared direct to spindles, and "change gear" gear trains) were developed over the centuries, with some of those elements being quite ancient.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] Various sparks of inventive power during the Middle Ages and Renaissance combined some of these elements into screw-making machines that presaged the industrial era to follow.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] These two classes of machine tools simultaneously took the various classes of screws and moved them, for the first time, from the category of expensive, hand-made, seldom-used objects into the category of affordable, often-interchangeable commodity.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] (The interchangeability developed gradually, from intra-company to inter-company to national to international).
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] Between 1800 and 1840, on the machine-screw side, it became common practice to build all of the relevant screw-cutting machine elements into engine lathes, so the term "screw-cutting lathe" ceased to stand in contradistinction to other metalworking lathe types as a "special" kind of lathe.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] Meanwhile, on the wood-screw side, hardware manufacturers had developed for their own in-house use the first fully automatic [mechanically automated] special-purpose machine tools for the making of screws.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] The 1760–1840 development arc was a tremendous technological advance, but later advancements would make screws even cheaper and more prevalent yet again.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] These began in the 1840s with the adaptation of the engine lathe with a turret-head toolholder to create the turret lathe.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] This development greatly reduced the time, effort, and skill needed from the machine operator to produce each machine screw.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] Single-pointing was forgone in favor of die head cutting for such medium- and high-volume repetitive production.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] Then, in the 1870s, the turret lathe's part-cutting cycle (sequence of movements) was automated by being put under cam control, in a way very similar to how music boxes and player pianos can play a tune automatically.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] According to Rolt (1965), the first person to develop such a machine was Christopher Miner Spencer, a New England inventor.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] Charles Vander Woerd may have contemporarily independently invented a machine similar to Spencer's.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] However, the wood-screw-making machines of the 1840s and 1850s [special-purpose factory production machine tools as opposed to small-machine-shop machine tools], such as those developed by Cullen Whipple of the New England Screw Company and Thomas J.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] Sloan of the American Screw Company, had anticipated the machines of Spencer and Vander Woerd in various ways, albeit approaching the problem of automated screw production from a different commercial angle.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] The nomenclatural evolution whereby the term "screw machine" is often used more narrowly than that is discussed above.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] Spencer patented his idea in 1873; but his patent failed to protect the cam drum, which Spencer called the 'brain wheel'.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] Therefore, many other people quickly took up the idea.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] Later important developers of fully automatic lathes included S.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] Worsley, who developed a single-spindle machine for Brown & Sharpe, Edwin C.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] Henn, Reinhold Hakewessel, and George O.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] Gridley, who developed multiple-spindle variants and who was involved with a succession of corporations (Acme, National, National-Acme, Windsor Machine Company, Acme-Gridley, New Britain-Gridley); Edward P.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] Bullard Jr, who led the development of the Bullard Mult-Au-Matic; F.C.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] Schaum, who developed the Fay automatic lathe; Ralph Flanders and his brother Ernest, who further refined the Fay lathe and developed the automatic screw thread grinder.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] Meanwhile, engineers in Switzerland were also developing new manually and automatically controlled lathes.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] There, local innovators also developed further tooling for the machines and built clone machine models.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] The development of numerical control was the next major leap in the history of automatic lathes—and it is also what changed the paradigm of what the "manual versus automatic" distinction meant.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] Beginning in the 1950s, NC lathes began to replace manual lathes and cam-op screw machines, although the displacement of the older technology by CNC has been a long, gradual arc that even today is not a total eclipse.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] By the 1980s, true CNC screw machines (as opposed to simpler CNC lathes), Swiss-style and non-Swiss, had begun to make serious inroads into the realm of cam-op screw machines.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] Similarly, CNC chuckers were developed, eventually evolving even into CNC rotary transfer machines.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/automatic-lathe] These machine tools are little known outside the automotive manufacturing sector.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/edward-p-bullard-jr] Bullard was born in Columbus, Ohio, as son of Edward Payson Bullard Sr. and Alice Martha (Camp) Bullard.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/edward-p-bullard-jr] After attending Williston Seminary until 1891, he studied at Amherst College from 1890 to 1892.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/edward-p-bullard-jr] After his graduation he spent his entire career at Bridgeport Machine Tool Co.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/edward-p-bullard-jr] Bullard Jr. continued the family machine tool business and brought the turret principle to the vertical boring mill, making it a vertical turret lathe.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/edward-p-bullard-jr] He led the development of the company's multiple-spindle Mult-Au-Matic brand machine that became an important automatic lathe in the mass production of parts for the automotive industry.
[src:edward-p-bullard-jr/edward-p-bullard-jr] He was president of the company for 40 years, through World War I, the interwar period, and World War II, a period during which the Bullard company was the largest machine tool builder in the U.S., and vast volumes of military matériel were produced by countless companies running Bullard machines.
